{
  "texts": [
    "This gives us an intuition on the role of the prior π: the bound will be tight if there is a θ such that r(θ) and 1/π(θ) are small simulataneously.",
    "However, π cannot be large everywhere: its total mass is constrained to be 1.",
    "The larger Θ is, the more we have to \"spread the mass\" of π, which will increase 1/π(θ) in the bound.",
    "This is clear if we use a uniform prior: π(θ) = 1/M.",
    "In this case, the choice λ = 8n log(M/δ)/C 2 actually minimizes the right-hand side, and leads to:"
  ]
}